The world has seen over 450 coup attempts since 1950. Almost half succeeded.

By Will Jarrett

On 6th January, rioters stormed the Capitol building and took control of the seat of US democracy for several hours. A swathe of political commentators and national security experts immediately labelled the attack an attempted coup, and nearly as many others immediately dismissed their claims as fanciful.

So could a coup really take place in the US in 2021?

Jonathan Powell, professor of political science at the University of Central Florida, has created a database of attempted coups since 1950. He defines coups as “illegal and overt attempts by the military or other elites within the state apparatus to unseat the sitting executive.” To be “successful,” they must last at least seven days.

This database shows that roughly 2.4 billion people live in a country that has endured a successful coup in the last 70 years. There have been 476 coup attempts since 1950 – and almost exactly half succeeded. While people who live in stable areas of the world may like to believe that coups are a thing of the past, they are far from uncommon.

Africa has seen the most coup attempts and Oceania the least

The peak for coups came in the 1960s, at the height of the Cold War. But there have still been 53 coup attempts in just the past twenty years, 24 of which were successful.

If the Capitol attack had led to the overthrow of US democracy, it would not even have been the first successful North American coup since 2000 – that dubious honor goes to Honduras in 2009. And a 2016 study shows that coups against democracies are not especially unusual; although people in democracies typically have less reason to overthrow a leader, those regimes are less able to suppress dissent when it does arise.

Still, there are reasons to feel hopeful that a coup in the US is unlikely. Although North America has seen more coup attempts than both Oceania and Europe, its coups have been focused on Central America and the Caribbean. What is more, the rate of successful coups appears to be decreasing since a peak at the start of the century.

Successful coups are becoming less common but they are hardly rare

Although the US has been insulated from coups on its own territory in recent history, it nonetheless has a rather ignoble past when it comes to coups around the world.

A recent study from Lindsey O’Rourke, professor of political science at Boston University, found that the US had conducted at least 70 operations to effect regime change in foreign countries between 1943–2000.

Just on the US’s doorstep in Central America, the US has supported regime change in no fewer than seven countries since 1950.

The US has promoted regime change in the majority of its neighbors

Coups are far more frequent than many might expect, in no small part due to the US’s enthusiastic sponsorship of regime change around the world since at least the end of World War II. While the storming of the Capitol may have seemed like a terrifying outlier to US citizens, violent regime change is, in a wider sense, as American as apple pie.
